#. </p><h3>
msgctxt "dn28:25.1"
msgid "1.5. Dassanasamāpattidesanā"
msgstr "Attainments of Vision"

#. </h3><p><a class="sc" id="18"></a><a class="wp" id="wp7"></a>
msgctxt "dn28:26.1"
msgid ""
"Aparaṃ pana, bhante, etadānuttariyaṃ, yathā bhagavā dhammaṃ deseti "
"dassanasamāpattīsu."
msgstr ""
"And moreover, sir, how the Buddha teaches the attainments of vision is "
"unsurpassable."

msgctxt "dn28:26.2"
msgid "Catasso imā, bhante, dassanasamāpattiyo."
msgstr "There are these four attainments of vision."

msgctxt "dn28:26.3"
msgid ""
"Idha, bhante, ekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā ātappamanvāya padhānamanvāya "
"anuyogamanvāya appamādamanvāya sammāmanasikāramanvāya tathārūpaṃ "
"cetosamādhiṃ phusati, yathāsamāhite citte imameva kāyaṃ uddhaṃ pādatalā adho "
"kesamatthakā tacapariyantaṃ pūraṃ nānappakārassa asucino paccavekkhati:"
msgstr ""
"Firstly, some ascetic or brahmin—by dint of keen, resolute, committed, and "
"diligent effort, and right focus—experiences an immersion of the heart of "
"such a kind that they examine their own body up from the soles of the feet "
"and down from the tips of the hairs, wrapped in skin and full of many kinds "
"of filth."

msgctxt "dn28:26.4"
msgid ""
"‘atthi imasmiṃ kāye kesā lomā nakhā dantā taco maṃsaṃ nhāru aṭṭhi "
"aṭṭhimiñjaṃ vakkaṃ hadayaṃ yakanaṃ kilomakaṃ pihakaṃ papphāsaṃ antaṃ "
"antaguṇaṃ udariyaṃ karīsaṃ pittaṃ semhaṃ pubbo lohitaṃ sedo medo assu vasā "
"kheḷo siṅghānikā lasikā muttan’ti."
msgstr ""
"‘In this body there is head hair, body hair, nails, teeth, skin, flesh, "
"sinews, bones, bone marrow, kidneys, heart, liver, diaphragm, spleen, lungs, "
"intestines, mesentry, undigested food, feces, bile, phlegm, pus, blood, "
"sweat, fat, tears, grease, saliva, snot, synovial fluid, urine.’ "

msgctxt "dn28:26.5"
msgid "Ayaṃ paṭhamā dassanasamāpatti."
msgstr "This is the first attainment of vision."

#. </p><p><a class="sc" id="19"></a><a class="pts" id="pts3.105"></a>
msgctxt "dn28:27.1"
msgid "Puna caparaṃ, bhante, idhekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā ātappamanvāya …"
msgstr "Furthermore, some ascetic or brahmin attains that and goes beyond it."

